{
  "response_text": "Across all simulation runs, the cumulative number of prey deaths increases monotonically from zero at initialization, exhibiting a rapid acceleration phase followed by a marked deceleration as the maximum cumulative count is approached. During the initial 500 time steps, death counts rise steeply, with most simulations accumulating between 200 and 230 deaths by step 500. The rate of mortality then slows considerably between steps 500 and 1000, with cumulative totals reaching approximately 240 deaths. By steps 1000 to 1500, the accumulation of deaths largely ceases across most runs, with final cumulative death counts stabilizing at values ranging from approximately 220 to 250. This plateauing indicates the depletion of the prey population, as the initial population was set to 250 individuals. Some runs exhibit slower mortality trajectories, with one simulation reaching only approximately 15 deaths by step 200 and accumulating roughly 235 total deaths by step 1800, while others reach 245 deaths by step 1200. The final cumulative counts approaching the initial population size suggest near-complete mortality of the founding prey population across all replicates, with minor stochastic variation in the timing of extinction and final death tallies."
}

